thread.title: Obama to start selling Pacific trade deal
thread.title_full: Obama to start selling Pacific trade deal

author: democratandchronicle.com
title: Obama to start selling Pacific trade deal
text:
President Obama has a new long-term sales project in the Trans-Pacific Partnership. Obama's efforts ramp up Tuesday when he travels to the Department of Agriculture to meet with business leaders about the proposed trade deal involving the United States and 11 other Pacific Rim countries.
In making this and future appearances, Obama will be seeking to sway Congress as it decides whether or not to ratify the deal.
The president will also be lobbying against critics -- including some fellow Democrats -- who say the trade deal will lead to export of American jobs overseas.
Congress must sign off on the deal before it takes effect.
"Our goal here is going to be to talk about the benefits of the agreement," said White House spokesman Josh Earnest, adding that the deal "expands access to overseas markets for products that are stamped Made in America."
It's no accident that Obama will be selling the Pacific trade agreement at the Agriculture Department.
Earnest said the proposal would eliminate some 18,000 tariffs and taxes on a variety of U.S. exports, including agricultural products ranging from soybeans to poultry.
"Agriculture in the United States benefits significantly from the terms of this agreement," Earnest said.
Meanwhile, Earnest added, the administration is also reaching out to Capitol Hill about the Trans-Pacific Partnership.
"There have been a number of conversations that have already occurred between senior administrations officials and leading legislators," he said.
